
[1]sheath

   SHEATH, n.

   1. A case for the reception of a sword or other long and slender
   instrument; a scabbard. A sheath is that which separates, and hence a
   defense.

   2. In botany, a membrane investing a stem or branch, as in grasses.

   3. Any thin covering for defense; the wing-case of an insect.

   SHEATH, v.t.
